04281nam a22006855i 9780814789124DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147891247 a10.18574/nyu/9780814789124.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547341  a(OCoLC)751978626  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE209b.Y684 2011eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a973.32221 aYoung, Alfred F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhose American Revolution Was It? :bHistorians Interpret the Founding /cAlfred F. Young, Gregory Nobles. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tAmerican Historians Confront “Th e Transforming Hand of Revolution” -- tHistorians Extend the Reach of the American Revolution -- tAfterword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe meaning of the American Revolution has always been a much-contested question, and asking it is particularly important today: the standard, easily digested narrative puts the Founding Fathers at the head of a unified movement, failing to acknowledge the deep divisions in Revolutionary-era society and the many different historical interpretations that have followed. Whose American Revolution Was It? speaks both to the ways diverse groups of Americans who lived through the Revolution might have answered that question and to the different ways historians through the decades have interpreted the Revolution for our own time. As the only volume to offer an accessible and sweeping discussion of the period’s historiography and its historians, Whose American Revolution Was It? is an essential reference for anyone studying early American history. The first section, by Alfred F. Young, begins in 1925 with historian J. Franklin Jameson and takes the reader through the successive schools of interpretation up to the 1990s. The second section, by Gregory H. Nobles, focuses primarily on the ways present-day historians have expanded our understanding of the broader social history of the Revolution, bringing onto the stage farmers and artisans, who made up the majority of white men, as well as African Americans, Native Americans, and women of all social classes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aNobles, Gregory H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNobles, Gregory, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aYoung, Alfred F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479710540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814789124.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814789124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814789124/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK